Based on the description, here's the TikZ code that visually represents the definition of \(x_p^{\pm}\) and \(y_p^{\pm}\) for a pixel \(p\) in a poorly textured region:
```latex
\documentclass[tikz,border=3.14mm]{standalone}
\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[
    pixel/.style={draw, thick, minimum size=1cm},
    central_pixel/.style={pixel, fill=blue!30},
    neighbor_pixel/.style={pixel, fill=orange!50},
    label/.style={font=\small}
]
% Draw 5x5 pixel grid
\foreach \i in {-2,...,2} {
    \foreach \j in {-2,...,2} {
        \ifnum\i=0 \ifnum\j=0
            \node[central_pixel] at (\i,\j) {};
        \else
            \ifnum\i=1 \ifnum\j=0
                \node[neighbor_pixel] at (\i,\j) {};
            \else\ifnum\i=-1 \ifnum\j=0
                \node[neighbor_pixel] at (\i,\j) {};
            \else\ifnum\i=0 \ifnum\j=1
                \node[neighbor_pixel] at (\i,\j) {};
            \else\ifnum\i=0 \ifnum\j=-1
                \node[neighbor_pixel] at (\i,\j) {};
            \else
                \node[pixel, fill=gray!20] at (\i,\j) {};
            \fi\fi\fi\fi\fi
        \fi
    }
}
% Label central pixel
\node[label] at (0,0) {$p$};
% Label neighbor pixels
\node[label] at (1,0) {$x_p^+$};
\node[label] at (-1,0) {$x_p^-$};
\node[label] at (0,1) {$y_p^+$};
\node[label] at (0,-1) {$y_p^-$};
% Draw arrows indicating problematic pixels
\foreach \i in {-2,...,2} {
    \foreach \j in {-2,...,2} {
        \ifnum\i=0 \ifnum\j=0 \else
            \ifnum\i=1 \ifnum\j=0 \else
                \ifnum\i=-1 \ifnum\j=0 \else
                    \ifnum\i=0 \ifnum\j=1 \else
                        \ifnum\i=0 \ifnum\j=-1 \else
                            \draw[->, orange!70!black, thick, shorten >=2pt, shorten <=2pt] 
                                (0,0) to (\i,\j);
                        \fi\fi
                    \fi\fi
                \fi\fi
            \fi\fi
        \fi
    }
}
% Add caption
\node[align=center, font=\small] at (0,-3) {
    Definition of $x_p^{\pm}$ and $y_p^{\pm}$ for pixel $p$ \\
    in a poorly textured region. Orange points show pixels \\
    that may cause errors in $\Delta x_p$ and $\Delta y_p$ estimation.
};
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```
**Key Features:**
1. **Grid Structure:** 
   - 5x5 pixel grid with central pixel at (0,0)
   - Gray background pixels (fill=gray!20)
   - Central pixel highlighted in blue (fill=blue!30)
   - Immediate neighbor pixels highlighted in orange (fill=orange!50)
2. **Labeling:**
   - Central pixel labeled as "$p$"
   - Neighbor pixels labeled as:
     - Right: $x_p^+$
     - Left: $x_p^-$
     - Top: $y_p^+$
     - Bottom: $y_p^-$
3. **Visual Indicators:**
   - Orange arrows from central pixel to all non-immediate neighbors
   - These arrows represent "problematic pixels" that may cause estimation errors
4. **Caption:**
   - Multi-line caption explaining the diagram
   - Matches the provided description about poorly textured regions
**Output Description:**
- The central blue pixel represents the pixel of interest $p$
- The four immediate neighbors (up, down, left, right) are highlighted in orange
- All other pixels in the 5x5 grid are shown in gray
- Orange arrows point from the central pixel to all non-immediate neighbors, indicating these are the pixels that may cause errors in displacement estimation ($\Delta x_p$ and $\Delta y_p$)
This diagram visually represents how in poorly textured regions, the lack of distinct texture features makes it difficult to accurately estimate pixel displacements, as errors can be caused by distant pixels that happen to have similar intensity values.

